SIMPLE: nib
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Nib
<hw>Nib</hw> <pr>(n⟦icr⟧b)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[A variabt of
<ets>neb</ets>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A small and pointed thing or
part; a point; a prong.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧The little <xex>nib</xex> or
fructifying principle.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>Sir T. Browne.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>The bill or beak of a bird; the
neb.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>The points of a pen; also, the pointed part of a
pen; a short pen adapted for insertion in a holder.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>One of the handles which project from a scythe
snath;</def> <specif>also,</specif> <mark>[Prov. Eng.]</mark>, <def>the
shaft of a wagon.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <pluf>pl.</pluf> <def>See <cref>his nibs</cref>,
below.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>his nibs</b></col> <cd>Someone who gives a command or
makes a demand, often one who acts in a self-important manner, sometimes
one with authority; -- used mockingly as a jocose term, as if a title of
honor, but not usually in the presence of the person referred to, and
usually indicating resentment or contempt.</cd>
<mark>[Colloq.]</mark></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Nib</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Nib
<hw>Nib</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Nebbed</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Nibbing</conjf>.]</vmorph> <def>To furnish with a nib; to point;
to mend the point of; <as>as, to <ex>nib</ex> a pen</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Nibbed</ent>⟦br⟧
